SIMPLE: trawl
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Trawl
<hw>Trawl</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>trauler</ets>, <ets>troller</ets>, F. <ets>tr⟦ocir⟧ter</ets>, to
drag about, to stroll about; probably of Teutonic origin. Cf.
<er>Troll</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <def>To take fish, or other
marine animals, with a trawl.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trawl</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Trawl
<hw>Trawl</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A fishing line, often
extending a mile or more, having many short lines bearing hooks attached
to it. It is used for catching cod, halibut, etc.; a boulter.</def>
<mark>[U. S. & Canada]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A large bag net attached to a beam with iron frames
at its ends, and dragged at the bottom of the sea, -- used in fishing,
and in gathering forms of marine life from the sea bottom.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trawlboat</ent>⟦br⟧
